Pages = {{108-111}},
Month = {{JUL 1}},
Abstract = {{Human memory is strikingly susceptible to social influences, yet we know
   little about the underlying mechanisms. We examined how socially induced
   memory errors are generated in the brain by studying the memory of
   individuals exposed to recollections of others. Participants exhibited a
   strong tendency to conform to erroneous recollections of the group,
   producing both long-lasting and temporary errors, even when their
   initial memory was strong and accurate. Functional brain imaging
   revealed that social influence modified the neuronal representation of
   memory. Specifically, a particular brain signature of enhanced amygdala
   activity and enhanced amygdala-hippocampus connectivity predicted
   long-lasting but not temporary memory alterations. Our findings reveal
   how social manipulation can alter memory and extend the known functions
   of the amygdala to encompass socially mediated memory distortions.}},
