Title = {{Reflex reading epilepsy: Effect of linguistic characteristics on spike
   frequency}},
Journal = {{EPILEPSY \& BEHAVIOR}},
Year = {{2011}},
Volume = {{20}},
Number = {{4}},
Pages = {{659-667}},
Month = {{APR}},
Abstract = {{Reading epilepsy is a rare reflex epilepsy in which seizures are
   provoked by reading. Several cases have been described in the
   literature, but the pathophysiological processes vary widely and remain
   unclear. We describe a 42-year-old male patient with reading epilepsy
   evaluated using clinical assessments and continuous video/EEG
   recordings. We administered verbal, nonverbal, and reading tasks to
   determine factors precipitating seizures. Linguistic characteristics of
   the words were manipulated. Results indicated that reading-induced
   seizures were significantly more numerous than those observed during
   verbal and nonverbal tasks. In reading tasks, spike frequency
   significantly increased with involvement of the phonological reading
   route. Spikes were recorded predominantly in left parasagittal regions.
   Future cerebral imaging studies will enable us to visualize the spatial
   localization and temporal course of reading-induced seizures and brain
   activity involved in reading. A better understanding of reading epilepsy
   is crucial for reading rehabilitation in these patients. (C) 2011
   Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.}},
