   autism, and healthy individuals}},
Journal = {{FRONTIERS IN HUMAN NEUROSCIENCE}},
Year = {{2011}},
Volume = {{5}},
Month = {{FEB 2}},
Abstract = {{In this paper we show how we empirically tested one of the most relevant
   topics in philosophy of mind through a series of fMRI experiments: the
   classification of different types of intention. To this aim, firstly we
   trace a theoretical distinction among private, prospective, and
   communicative intentions. Second, we propose a set of predictions
   concerning the recognition of these three types of intention in healthy
   individuals, and we report the experimental results corroborating our
   theoretical model of intention. Third, we derive from our model
   predictions relevant for the domain of psychopathological functioning.
   In particular, we treat the cases of both hyper-intentionality (as in
   paranoid schizophrenia) and hypo-intentionality (as in autistic spectrum
   disorders). Our conclusion is that the theoretical model of intention we
   propose contributes to enlarge our knowledge on the neurobiological
   bases of intention processing, in both healthy people and in people with
   impairments to the neurocognitive system that underlies intention
   recognition.}},
