Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{1-7}},
Month = {{FEB}},
Abstract = {{This study aimed to investigate the differences in brain functions
   during verbal working memory between individuals with alcohol use
   disorders (AUD) and normal controls. fMRI was used to scan brain
   activations associated with verbal working memory while participants
   performed 2-back and 0-back tasks. A total of 21 young male college
   students participated in the study. Eleven of those who clinically met
   the criteria for AUD were assigned to the AUD group, whereas ten
   demographically similar subjects who were social drinkers but not AUD
   were assigned to the normal control group. The AUD group showed less
   activation in bilateral frontal and precentral, left superior temporal,
   left superior parietal, and left cerebellar cortex during the 2-back
   task relative to 0-back task compared to the normal control group. In
   contrast, the control group showed less activation only in the right
   uncus than the AUD group. These results suggest that subjects with AUD
   present abnormality in brain functioning during verbal working memory.}},
